06240nam a22009135i 9780226681368DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2019052058  a97802266813687 a10.7208/97802266813682doi  a(DE-B1597)549566  a(OCoLC)1202454554  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aJC575b.D49 2020 4aJC575b.D49 2020 7aPOL0000002bisacsh04a320.01/122300aDifference without Domination :bPursuing Justice in Diverse Democracies /ced. by Danielle Allen, Rohini Somanathan. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (368 p.) :b1 halftone, 10 line drawings  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tPart 1 Difference without Domination -- t1 A New Theory of Justice -- t2 Race, Domination, and Republicanism -- tPart 2 Relations before Transactions: New Approaches to Inequality, Justice, & Dignity -- t3 Crime and Punishment in a Divided Society -- t4 The Psychology of Implicit Intergroup Bias and the Prospect of Change -- t5 Human Dignity and Modern Democracies -- t6 Relations before Transactions -- tPart 3 The Limits of Mirroring: New Approaches to Representation, Measurement, & Membership -- t7 Overrepresentation -- t8 Second-Order Diversity -- t9 Contributing to a Society of Equals -- t10 The Measurement and Mismeasurement of Social Difference -- t11 Immigration, Membership, and Justice -- tConclusion -- tIndex -- tAuthor Bios0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAround the globe, democracy appears broken. With political and socioeconomic inequality on the rise, we are faced with the urgent question of how to better distribute power, opportunity, and wealth in diverse modern societies. This volume confronts the dilemma head-on, exploring new ways to combat current social hierarchies of domination. Using examples from the United States, India, Germany, and Cameroon, the contributors offer paradigm-changing approaches to the concepts of justice, identity, and social groups while also taking a fresh look at the idea that the demographic make-up of institutions should mirror the make-up of a populace as a whole. After laying out the conceptual framework, the volume turns to a number of provocative topics, among them the pernicious tenacity of implicit bias, the logical contradictions inherent to the idea of universal human dignity, and the paradoxes and problems surrounding affirmative action. A stimulating blend of empirical and interpretive analyses, Difference without Domination urges us to reconsider the idea of representation and to challenge what it means to measure equality and inequality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aCultural pluralism. 0aDemocracy. 0aEquality. 0aJustice. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  ademocracy.  adignity.  adiversity.  aidentity.  aimplicit bias.  ajustice.  anondomination.  arace.  asocial groups.  astatistical mirroring.1 aAllen, Danielle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAllen, Danielle, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBanaji, Mahzarin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGerken, Heather K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLai, Calvin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLindner, Urs, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLoury, Glenn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLópez-Guerra, Claudio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRogers, Melvin L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/